The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt during the last G-7 summit at Ise-Shima in Japan.
At the next meeting of the leaders of the world's developed economies, no one can say which of them will be among the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump might represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen might represent France.
They could sit alongside British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could make themselves the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has been going on for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend seemed to be towards convergence, and people seemed to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's illustrated this type of globalization: breaking into stores of this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But in recent times, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is becoming increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand less and less the foreigners.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are becoming increasingly pointed), companies are relocating their production closer to the markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens international trade growth.
Such an "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded with Japanese cars. They then began producing these cars domestically.
Currently, most "Japanese" automobiles sold in the United States are manufactured in the United States. But the reversal of globalisation of goods is now easier than ever, thanks to the progress of robotics engineering and the development of processes such as 3D printing.
Thus, the current criticism of globalisation is more inclined to focus on non-commercial issues.
However, this evolution does not only reflect the slowdown of trade growth.
Consumers in wealthy countries are much more at ease with foreign products, and in some cases, they are even dependent on them, since constantly updated electronics and affordable "ephemeral" fashion have become dominant in advanced economies.
Rather than rejecting foreign products, the current opponents of globalisation reject foreigners.
Disputes over investor protection clauses in commercial agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on the problems of obscure tribunals protecting foreign companies' interests and allegedly infringing on national sovereignty.
Next comes the global refugee crisis: in Europe in particular, the anxiety over this influx may be a harbinger of a broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why are the populations of advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
It's not as if they had never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries constantly travel to distant destinations and hundreds of millions of people from all over the world head towards advanced countries every year.
The problem lies in our way of traveling.
Today, we tend to experience things in a fast and superficial way, rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a unique interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If the participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper understanding or more profound cooperation base.
Continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of a superficial approach to current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restoration establishments are reluctant to provide good or simply honest service to people who will certainly never come back.
Restaurants serve mediocre food (or worse) without a smile, taxi drivers scam you, and hotel owners lie about their equipment.
Moreover, this small game can be interrupted.
On sites where tourism has become a source of foreign income, it has also become a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or Red Sea tourist complexes are enough to trigger a deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The emblem of modern tourism is a massive cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (visiting a beautiful Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean ship Harmony of the Seas aims to recreate all the world's climates.
In fact, this over 30 meter long ship than the Eiffel Tower contains a tropical park and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Bus or train tourism companies do the same to ensure the security of their clients, by releasing them on a famous site only for a limited time, in fact, just long enough to take a few photos.
This type of travel puts a constraint on the capacity of local infrastructure.
Often, there is not enough space to walk along the canals of Venice or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces the poor mutual understanding.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, meeting only scammers who offer them trinkets or expensive taxi rides.
The indigenous people do not particularly appreciate the groups of tourists that gather around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor does anyone maintain a relationship of trust.
It is easy to feel some nostalgia for that time when tourism went hand in hand with long stays and long-term encounters with very different cultures.
It would be obviously impossible, for the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or months in old monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for example, can provide a much more appealing experience than a hotel or, worse, a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7, living and working for an extended period of time in a foreign country?
Not long after the United States entered World War II, Winston Churchill made that famous gesture of setting up camp to move in at the White House for 24 days to consolidate the transatlantic alliance of Great Britain, deepening its relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity might well be the greatest enemy of current anti-globalists populists.
